06/01/2004
WASHINGTON, United States -- Turkey's Recep Tayyip Erdogan is due to make his first visit to Washington as prime minister on 26 January. 
According to US media, he and President George W. 
Bush would discuss the war on international terrorism, bilateral economic co-operation, efforts to reunite Cyprus, Ankara's hosting of the NATO summit in June, and its bid to join the EU. 
The two leaders are also expected to discuss the situation in Iraq.
In other news, the Turkish military denied reports that it was at odds with the government over a new plan for the reunification of Cyprus. 
Local media reported that the General Staff was objecting to a foreign ministry draft based on UN Secretary General Kofi Annan's plan. 
Justice Minister and government spokesman Cemil Cicek said Monday that Turkey wants negotiations to resume on the basis of Annan's plan. 
(AP, AFP, Anadolu Agency, NTV, TRT 2 - 05/01/04)
